Fuel Systems,Emission Control,Creation of emissions,Sources of emission ,"Emissions from a fuel-driven motor vehicle usually come from four sources: the fuel tank, the carburetor, the crankcase, and the exhaust system.",Theory,emissionsys_2.html,emissionsys_pc.html,emissionsys_kc.html,,,HA397_2.pdf
Fuel Systems,Emission Control,Creation of emissions,Combustion ,"To reduce exhaust emissions, some devices or systems control the combustion process itself, while others treat the resulting exhaust gases. Most modern vehicles use a combination.",Theory,combustion_2.html,combustion_pc.html,combustion_kc.html,,,HA398_2.pdf
Fuel Systems,Emission Control,Types of emissions,Hydrocarbons ,Hydrocarbons are a major component of motor vehicle emissions. Hydrocarbon emissions react with other compounds in the atmosphere to produce photo-chemical smog.,Theory,hydrocarbons_2.html,hydrocarbons_pc.html,hydrocarbons_kc.html,,,HA400_2.pdf
Fuel Systems,Emission Control,Types of emissions,Hydrocarbons in exhaust gases ,"Hydrocarbon emissions in the exhaust gases can be caused by valve overlap, incomplete combustion and ignition system misfiring.",Theory,hydrocarbonemissions_2.html,hydrocarbonemissions_pc.html,hydrocarbonemissions_kc.html,,,HA401_2.pdf
Fuel Systems,Emission Control,Types of emissions,Oxides of nitrogen ,"Under the high temperatures and pressure of combustion, nitrogen from the air combines with oxygen to produce oxides of nitrogen. Oxides of nitrogen can be produced in any operating internal combustion engine.",Theory,nitrogenoxide_2.html,nitrogenoxide_pc.html,nitrogenoxide_kc.html,,,HA402_2.pdf
Fuel Systems,Emission Control,Types of emissions,Particulates ,"In spark-ignition engines, particulates are caused by incomplete combustion of rich air-fuel mixtures. In compression-ignition engines, they are caused by a lack of turbulence and lack of oxygen.",Theory,particulates_2.html,particulates_pc.html,particulates_kc.html,,,HA403_2.pdf
Fuel Systems,Emission Control,Types of emissions,Carbon monoxide ,Carbon monoxide is produced during combustion when there are not enough oxygen molecules around the hydrocarbon molecules. This can be caused by an incorrect air-fuel ratio. Carbon monoxide is an extremely poisonous gas.,Theory,carbmnoxd_2.html,carbmnoxd_pc.html,carbmnoxd_kc.html,,,HA404_2.pdf
Fuel Systems,Emission Control,Types of emissions,Carbon dioxide ,"When complete combustion of air and fuel occurs, carbon dioxide and water are produced.",Theory,carbdioxd_2.html,carbdioxd_pc.html,carbdioxd_kc.html,,,HA405_2.pdf
Fuel Systems,Emission Control,Emission control,Evaporation emission control ,"A positive crankcase ventilation system flushes vapors from the crankcase into the intake manifold, to join with the inlet air-fuel mixture. Once there, the vapors are drawn into the engine for burning.",Theory,evaporation_2.html,evaporation_pc.html,evaporation_kc.html,,,HA407_2.pdf
Fuel Systems,Emission Control,Emission control,Catalytic conversion ,"Maintaining the stoichiometric ratio is necessary for a catalytic converter to operate efficiently. It receives all the engine's exhaust gases, and chemically converts remaining pollutants to less harmful substances.",Theory,catalyticconversion_2.html,catalyticconversion_pc.html,catalyticconversion_kc.html,,,HA408_2.pdf
Fuel Systems,Emission Control,Emission control,Crankcase emission control ,"A PCV valve, controlled by manifold pressure, regulates gas flow between the crankcase and the inlet manifold. With the engine off, the valve is closed. Air cannot enter the inlet manifold. This allows the engine to start.",Theory,crankcase_2.html,crankcase_pc.html,crankcase_kc.html,,,HA411_2.pdf
Fuel Systems,Emission Control,On-board diagnostics,OBD systems ,On-Board Diagnostic systems use the vehicle's computers to detect problems with its emission components and other systems.,Theory,obdsystems_2.html,obdsystems_pc.html,obdsystems_kc.html,,,HA415_2.pdf
Fuel Systems,Emission Control,On-board diagnostics,Diagnostic trouble codes ,The diagnostic trouble codes inform the technician of the computers opinion of the location of a system fault.,Theory,diagnostictroublecodes_2.html,diagnostictroublecodes_pc.html,diagnostictroublecodes_kc.html,,,HA416_2.pdf
Fuel Systems,Emission Control,On-board diagnostics,Monitoring emissions,OBD II systems monitor the emission systems in a vehicle either 'continuously' or 'non-continuously'.,Theory,monitoremission_2.html,monitoremission_pc.html,monitoremission_kc.html,,,HA417_2.pdf
Fuel Systems,Emission Control,Emissions procedures,Checking & cleaning a PCV valve ,"Most modern vehicles have a PCV valve, which should be checked periodically to make sure that it is not clogged with deposits from the exhaust waste. The objective of this procedure is to show you how to check and clean the PCV valve part of the emission control system.",Procedure,pcvvalve_2.html,pcvvalve_pc.html,,,pcvvalve_WS_2.pdf,HA418_2.pdf
Fuel Systems,Emission Control,Emissions procedures,Obtaining & interpreting scan tool data,"The objective of this procedure is to show you how to retrieve, record and clear stored OBD I & II diagnostic trouble codes using a scan tool. Remember, when retrieving codes for an OBD I vehicle, clear the codes then start the vehicle and recheck for any codes that reset. When diagnosing and OBD II vehicle, do not clear the codes until the vehicle is repaired.",Procedure,cleardtc_2.html,cleardtc_pc.html,,,cleardtc_WS_2.pdf,HA419_2.pdf
Fuel Systems,Emission Control,Emission control tasksheets,C396: Diagnose engine operation concerns.,"Diagnose engine mechanical, electrical, electronic, fuel, and ignition concerns with an oscilloscope and/or engine diagnostic equipment; determine necessary action. ",Tasksheet,C396.pdf,,,,,
