Transmissions,Final Drive & Drive Shafts,Basic layouts,Rear-wheel drive layout ,"In a conventional rear-wheel drive layout, the engine and transmission are mounted longitudinally at the front of the vehicle and drive is transmitted to a rear axle assembly by a propeller shaft.",Theory,rwdlayout_2.html,rwdlayout_pc.html,rwdlayout_kc.html,,,HA653_2.pdf
Transmissions,Final Drive & Drive Shafts,Basic layouts,Four-wheel drive layout ,"In a conventional four-wheel drive vehicle, propeller shafts connect a transfer case at the rear of the transmission to final drive units on both front and rear axles.",Theory,4wdlayout_2.html,4wdlayout_pc.html,4wdlayout_kc.html,,,HA654_2.pdf
Transmissions,Final Drive & Drive Shafts,Basic layouts,All-wheel drive layout ,"In a conventional full-time four-wheel drive vehicle, a third differential is located in the transfer case.",Theory,ftime4wlayout_2.html,ftime4wlayout_pc.html,ftime4wlayout_kc.html,,,HA655_2.pdf
Transmissions,Final Drive & Drive Shafts,Front-wheel drive,Front-wheel drive shafts ,"In front-wheel drive vehicles, the drive shafts transfer the drive directly from the differential to the front wheels.",Theory,fwdshaft_2.html,fwdshaft_pc.html,fwdshaft_kc.html,,,HA658_2.pdf
Transmissions,Final Drive & Drive Shafts,Front-wheel drive,Front-wheel final drives ,"In front-wheel drive vehicles, the final drive gears are incorporated in the transaxle assembly.",Theory,fwdfinaldrive_2.html,fwdfinaldrive_pc.html,fwdfinaldrive_kc.html,,,HA659_2.pdf
Transmissions,Final Drive & Drive Shafts,Rear-wheel drive,Rear-wheel drive shafts ,"The propeller shaft transfers the drive from the transmission to the final drive. It is normally of a hollow, tubular construction.",Theory,rwdshaft_2.html,rwdshaft_pc.html,rwdshaft_kc.html,,,HA661_2.pdf
Transmissions,Final Drive & Drive Shafts,Rear-wheel drive,Universal joints ,The most common type of universal joint fitted to propeller shafts is known as a Hookes joint or a cross and roller joint.,Theory,universal_2.html,universal_pc.html,universal_kc.html,,,HA662_2.pdf
Transmissions,Final Drive & Drive Shafts,Rear-wheel drive,Rear-wheel final drive ,"In a conventional rear-wheel drive vehicle, a crownwheel and pinion transfers the drive through ninety degrees and provides a final gear reduction to the driving road wheels.",Theory,rwdfinaldrive_2.html,rwdfinaldrive_pc.html,rwdfinaldrive_kc.html,,,HA663_2.pdf
Transmissions,Final Drive & Drive Shafts,Final drives procedures,Checking free play ,"The objective of this procedure is to show you how to check a final drive unit for wear and free play. While final drive components must be held firmly in position by bearings and thrust washers, there must be operational clearance between meshing components. This check determines the amount of free movement between the crown wheel and pinion.",Procedure,checkfreeplay_2.html,checkfreeplay_pc.html,,,checkfreeplay_WS_2.pdf,HA675_2.pdf
Transmissions,Final Drive & Drive Shafts,Final drives procedures,Checking drive shaft joints,Drive shafts require joints at either end to allow for angular change. Drive shafts turn at high speed. The Universal and Constant Velocity Joints allow drive to be transmitted through an angular change. This requires the shafts to be well balanced with minimal free movement. The objective of this procedure is to show you how to check drive shaft joints for wear.,Procedure,chkdriveshaft_2.html,chkdriveshaft_pc.html,,,chkdriveshaft_WS_2.pdf,HA676_2.pdf
Transmissions,Final Drive & Drive Shafts,Final drives procedures,Checking manual transaxle/differential oil,The objective of this procedure is to show you how to check gearbox/differential oil for manual transmissions. You will need to refer to the owner's manual for exactly where to check the oil level.,Procedure,checkingdiffoil_2.html,checkingdiffoil_pc.html,,,checkingdiffoil_WS_2.pdf,HA677_2.pdf
